Unsupervised Learning: Trade&Ahead¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The stock market has consistently proven to be a good place to invest in and save for the future. There are a lot of compelling reasons to invest in stocks. It can help in fighting inflation, create wealth, and also provides some tax benefits. Good steady returns on investments over a long period of time can also grow a lot more than seems possible. Also, thanks to the power of compound interest, the earlier one starts investing, the larger the corpus one can have for retirement. Overall, investing in stocks can help meet life's financial aspirations.

It is important to maintain a diversified portfolio when investing in stocks in order to maximise earnings under any market condition. Having a diversified portfolio tends to yield higher returns and face lower risk by tempering potential losses when the market is down. It is often easy to get lost in a sea of financial metrics to analyze while determining the worth of a stock, and doing the same for a multitude of stocks to identify the right picks for an individual can be a tedious task. By doing a cluster analysis, one can identify stocks that exhibit similar characteristics and ones which exhibit minimum correlation. This will help investors better analyze stocks across different market segments and help protect against risks that could make the portfolio vulnerable to losses.

Objective¶

Trade&Ahead is a financial consultancy firm who provide their customers with personalized investment strategies. They have hired you as a Data Scientist and provided you with data comprising stock price and some financial indicators for a few companies listed under the New York Stock Exchange. They have assigned you the tasks of analyzing the data, grouping the stocks based on the attributes provided, and sharing insights about the characteristics of each group.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Ticker Symbol: An abbreviation used to uniquely identify publicly traded shares of a particular stock on a particular stock market
  • Company: Name of the company
  • GICS Sector: The specific economic sector assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • GICS Sub Industry: The specific sub-industry group assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • Current Price: Current stock price in dollars
  • Price Change: Percentage change in the stock price in 13 weeks
  • Volatility: Standard deviation of the stock price over the past 13 weeks
  • ROE: A measure of financial performance calculated by dividing net income by shareholders' equity (shareholders' equity is equal to a company's assets minus its debt)
  • Cash Ratio: The ratio of a company's total reserves of cash and cash equivalents to its total current liabilities
  • Net Cash Flow: The difference between a company's cash inflows and outflows (in dollars)
  • Net Income: Revenues minus expenses, interest, and taxes (in dollars)
  • Earnings Per Share: Company's net profit divided by the number of common shares it has outstanding (in dollars)
  • Estimated Shares Outstanding: Company's stock currently held by all its shareholders
  • P/E Ratio: Ratio of the company's current stock price to the earnings per share
  • P/B Ratio: Ratio of the company's stock price per share by its book value per share (book value of a company is the net difference between that company's total assets and total liabilities)

Questions:

  1. What does the distribution of stock prices look like?
  2. The stocks of which economic sector have seen the maximum price increase on average?
  3. How are the different variables correlated with each other?
  4. Cash ratio provides a measure of a company's ability to cover its short-term obligations using only cash and cash equivalents. How does the average cash ratio vary across economic sectors?
  5. P/E ratios can help determine the relative value of a company's shares as they signify the amount of money an investor is willing to invest in a single share of a company per dollar of its earnings. How does the P/E ratio vary, on average, across economic sectors?

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(df, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=df, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(df, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(df[feature])  # length of the column
    count = df[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=df,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=df[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

How are the different variables correlated with each other?¶

Current Price:

  • Positively correlated with Earnings Per Share (0.48) and P/E Ratio (0.26).
  • Mild positive correlation with Cash Ratio (0.13) and Price Change (0.13).
  • Mild negative correlation with Volatility (-0.12).

Price Change:

  • Strong negative correlation with Volatility (-0.41).
  • Mild positive correlations with Net Income (0.18), Earnings Per Share (0.18), and Cash Ratio (0.17).

Volatility:

  • Besides the strong negative correlation with Price Change (-0.41), it also has negative correlations with Earnings Per Share (-0.38) and Net Income (-0.38).
  • Mild positive correlation with ROE (0.16).

ROE (Return on Equity):

  • Positive correlation with Volatility (0.16).
  • Negative correlations with Earnings Per Share (-0.41), Net Income (-0.29), and Cash Ratio (-0.07).

Cash Ratio:

  • Positively correlated with Net Cash Flow (0.11).
  • Negligible or very weak correlations with most other variables.

Net Cash Flow:

  • Mild positive correlations with Cash Ratio (0.11) and Estimated Shares Outstanding (0.14).

Net Income:

  • Positively correlated with Earnings Per Share (0.56) and Estimated Shares Outstanding (0.59).
  • Negative correlations with Volatility (-0.38) and ROE (-0.29).

Earnings Per Share:

  • Strong positive correlation with Net Income (0.56).
  • Negative correlations with Volatility (-0.38) and ROE (-0.41).

Estimated Shares Outstanding:

  • Positive correlation with Net Income (0.59).
  • Mild negative correlation with Current Price (-0.15).

P/E Ratio:

  • Positively correlated with Current Price (0.26) and Volatility (0.26).
  • Negative correlations with Earnings Per Share (-0.26) and Net Income (-0.22).

P/B Ratio:

  • Mild positive correlations with Cash Ratio (0.23) and Current Price (0.12).

Cash ratio provides a measure of a company's ability to cover its short-term obligations using only cash and cash equivalents. How does the average cash ratio vary across economic sectors?¶

In [26]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
sns.barplot(data=df, x='GICS Sector', y='Cash Ratio', ci=False) 
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

Observations:¶

  • Information Technology: This sector has the highest average cash ratio, reaching around 130. This indicates that companies in this sector, on average, have a significant amount of cash and cash equivalents to cover their short-term obligations, suggesting a strong liquidity position.

  • Health Care: The next highest cash ratio is observed in the Health Care sector, averaging slightly below 100. This suggests that companies in this sector also have a favorable liquidity position, though not as robust as those in the Information Technology sector.

  • Telecommunications Services: This sector follows closely, with an average cash ratio just below the Health Care sector.

  • Consumer Staples and Utilities: These sectors have average cash ratios around 70 and 60, respectively. They showcase moderate liquidity positions, implying that companies in these sectors have a decent amount of cash and cash equivalents to meet their short-term obligations.

  • Real Estate, Materials, Consumer Discretionary, and Energy: These sectors have cash ratios ranging between 20 and 50. Companies in these sectors, on average, have a lower liquidity position compared to the sectors mentioned above.

  • Industrials and Financials: These sectors have the lowest average cash ratios, with Industrials slightly above 10 and Financials even lower. Companies in these sectors, on average, have the least amount of cash and cash equivalents relative to their short-term obligations, suggesting a more limited liquidity position.

In summary, the Information Technology sector demonstrates the strongest average liquidity position based on the cash ratio, followed by the Health Care and Telecommunications Services sectors. In contrast, the Industrials and Financials sectors appear to have the weakest liquidity positions on average.

K-means Clustering¶

Checking Elbow Plot¶

In [32]:
k_means_df = subset_scaled_df.copy()
In [33]:
clusters = range(1, 15)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1)
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    prediction = model.predict(k_means_df)
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(k_means_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / k_means_df.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=20)
plt.show()

In [47]:
# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"] 

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(hc_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(hc_df))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm
            
# printing the combination of distance metric and linkage method with the highest cophenetic correlation
print('*'*100)
print(
    "Highest cophenetic correlation is {}, which is obtained with {} distance and {} linkage.".format(
        high_cophenet_corr, high_dm_lm[0].capitalize(), high_dm_lm[1]
    )
)

Checking Dendrograms¶

In [49]:
# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"] ## code to add linkages

# lists to save results of cophenetic correlation calculation
compare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]
compare = []

# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# We will enumerate through the list of linkage methods above
# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(hc_df, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(hc_df))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

Overall Insights:¶

Cluster 0 represents a large group of stocks that have moderate current prices, a relatively high ROE, and a significant number of shares outstanding. The high cash ratio suggests strong liquidity positions, and the negative P/B ratio indicates that the market might undervalue these companies relative to their book values.

Cluster 1, on the other hand, consists of a single stock that has a very high current price, significant net income, and a high earnings per share. The stock also has a very high cash ratio, indicating a strong liquidity position, and a negative P/B ratio similar to Segment 0. The significant negative net cash flow suggests some caution.

  • Diversity: Cluster 0 is much more diverse in terms of both financial metrics and GICS sector representation. This cluster contains stocks from all sectors and a broad range of financial metrics.

  • Unique Stock in Cluster 1: The stock in Cluster 1 stands out in terms of several financial metrics. It has a higher current price, earnings per share, and other metrics. It belongs to the Consumer Discretionary sector.

  • Financial Characteristics: While Cluster 0 stocks are generally more moderate in their financial metrics, the stock in Cluster 1 tends to have superior metrics but also carries a significant negative net cash flow.

In conclusion, the Hierarchical Clustering has grouped a large and diverse set of stocks into Cluster 0, while isolating a single, distinct stock in Cluster 1. When considering investment or further analysis, it's essential to dive deeper into the specifics of these clusters, especially the unique stock in Cluster 1, and to consider other external factors and industry trends.

K-means vs Hierarchical Clustering¶

Execution Time:

  • While the exact time taken for both algorithms wasn't explicitly provided, typically, KMeans is faster, especially for large datasets. Hierarchical clustering tends to be more computationally intensive and could take longer for sizable datasets.

Number of Clusters:

  • KMeans Clustering: The algorithm identified 2 clusters.

  • Hierarchical Clustering: This too yielded 2 clusters.

  • Both methods agreed upon the number of clusters, which provides some consistency in the analysis.

Distinctiveness of Clusters:

  • KMeans Clustering: The clusters seemed to focus on different attributes. One cluster had stocks with higher prices, stable earnings, and positive net incomes. The other cluster had stocks with lower prices, higher volatility, and negative net incomes.

  • Hierarchical Clustering: While it also yielded two clusters, the distinction seemed primarily based on stock price values and a few financial metrics. One cluster had significantly high stock prices, and the other contained the majority of stocks with more varied financial indicators.

Number of Observations in Similar Clusters:

  • There is an overlap between the clusters identified by both methods. The cluster with higher stock values in both algorithms is consistent, albeit with different stock counts. The distinction between clusters in both techniques largely revolves around financial health, volatility, and stock prices.

Cluster Profiles:

  • KMeans Clustering: Gave a clear distinction between stocks with high value, stability, and positive net incomes versus those with significant price drops, high volatility, and negative net incomes.

  • Hierarchical Clustering: Offered a broader view, with one cluster heavily focused on high stock prices and another capturing a diverse range of financial attributes.

  • In terms of granularity and specificity, KMeans provided a more nuanced differentiation, especially when considering financial health.

Use Case Relevance:

  • KMeans Clustering: Given its efficiency and distinct clustering for this project, it may be more suitable for real-time or frequent stock data clustering for Trade&Ahead.

  • Hierarchical Clustering: Provides a hierarchical structure that can be insightful for understanding nested relationships, but might be overkill for this specific project unless we're interested in multiple levels of stock categorization.

Conclusion: Both KMeans and Hierarchical clustering provided valuable insights into the stock data. While they had some similarities in the clusters formed, the distinction and focus differed slightly. For Trade&Ahead's objectives, KMeans might be a more straightforward choice given its efficiency and the clarity of clusters it produced. However, Hierarchical clustering could be a complementary tool if there's interest in exploring nested relationships between stocks. It's essential to choose the clustering method based on the specific goals and computational resources at hand.
